    <!-- ===== DOOR LOCK (position actuator, MuJoCo-native PD) =====
         Position actuator with huge kp turns the door hinge into a
         joint state lock. MuJoCo computes the restoring force every
         physics step (500 Hz), so there is no feedback lag — the
         door is rigid:

           ctrl = 0   → kp*(0 - qpos) restoring + kv*(0 - qvel) damping.
                        With kp=20000, even a 1° displacement applies
                        ~349 Nm restoring — far more than any single
                        Go2W can exert. The door is wall-like.

           ctrl = qpos (live-tracking) → kp*(qpos - qpos) = 0 → the
                        actuator applies ~zero force. The door is
                        released and moves under its natural hinge
                        spring (stiffness 4.5 Nm/rad). Robot A can
                        push it normally.

         door_lock_from_button_node publishes the target of the
         door_barrier_lock actuator (below). The barrier is a real
         geometric obstacle — when extended (target=0) it physically
         blocks the doorway so no push force can get through. When
         the button is pressed the target slides to -3 and the barrier
         is tucked underground, leaving the door free to swing under
         its native FD30 spring physics.

         kv MUST be 0 — mujoco_ros2_control's POSITION-actuator
         detection in `mujoco_system.cpp` rejects any <position> with
         non-zero kv (the check `biasprm[2] == 0` is effectively
         `kv == 0`). All velocity damping is in the joint's own
         `damping="2000"` attribute above instead. -->
    <position name="door_barrier_lock" joint="door_barrier_slide"
              kp="20000" kv="0" ctrlrange="-0.1 3.1"/>
  </actuator>

